th an activist before abandoning both of them when he ended his covert deployment","width":"280"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396014698298/Bob-Lambert-009.jpg","typeData":{"source":"None","altText":"Bob Lambert","height":"180","credit":"None","caption":"Bob Lambert, the undercover officer who fathered a child with an activist before abandoning both of them when he ended his covert deployment","width":"300"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396014699419/Bob-Lambert-010.jpg","typeData":{"source":"None","altText":"Bob Lambert","height":"228","credit":"None","caption":"Bob Lambert, the undercover officer who fathered a child with an activist before abandoning both of them when he ended his covert deployment","width":"380"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396014700704/Bob-Lambert-011.jpg","typeData":{"source":"None","altText":"Bob Lambert","height":"276","credit":"None","caption":"Bob Lambert, the undercover officer who fathered a child with an activist before abandoning both of them when he ended his covert deployment","width":"460"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396014701836/Bob-Lambert-012.jpg","typeData":{"source":"None","altText":"Bob Lambert","height":"372","credit":"None","caption":"Bob Lambert, the undercover officer who fathered a child with an activist before abandoning both of them when he ended his covert deployment","width":"620"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396014703143/Bob-Lambert-013.jpg","typeData":{"source":"None","altText":"Bob Lambert","height":"1116","credit":"None","caption":"Bob Lambert, the undercover officer who fathered a child with an activist before abandoning both of them when he ended his covert deployment","width":"1860"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396014705020/Bob-Lambert-014.jpg","typeData":{"source":"None","altText":"Bob Lambert","height":"1536","credit":"None","caption":"Bob Lambert, the undercover officer who fathered a child with an activist before abandoning both of them when he ended his covert deployment","width":"2560"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396014700704/Bob-Lambert-011.jpg","typeData":{"source":"None","altText":"Bob Lambert","height":"276","credit":"None","caption":"Bob Lambert, the undercover officer who fathered a child with an activist before abandoning both of them when he ended his covert deployment","width":"460"}}]},{"id":"gu-image-433218895","relation":"thumbnail","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396014695115/Bob-Lambert-006.jpg","typeData":{"source":"None","altText":"Bob Lambert","height":"84","credit":"None","caption":"Bob Lambert, the undercover officer who fathered a child with an activist before abandoning both of them when he ended his covert deployment","width":"140"}},{"type":"image","mimeType":"image/jpeg","file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396014701836/Bob-Lambert-012.jpg","typeData":{"source":"None","altText":"Bob Lambert","height":"372","credit":"None","caption":"Bob Lambert, the undercover officer who fathered a child with an activist before abandoning both of them when he ended his covert deployment","width":"620"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Ten things we learned this week","webPublicationDate":"2014-03-28T13:26:40Z","sectionName":"UK news","sectionId":"uk-news","id":"uk-news/2014/mar/28/ten-things-we-learned-this-week","fields":{"shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3zvyj","standfirst":"<p>From Clegg v Farage to Paltrow minus Martin, via Egypt, Ed Miliband and the energy market – a roundup of the week's news<br></p>","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2014/mar/26/the-debate-for-europe-nick-clegg-v-nigel-farage-video-highlights\"                        data-show-ads=\"true\"                data-video-id=\"2066418\"                data-video-name=\"The debate for Europe: Nick Clegg v Nigel Farage - video highlights\"                data-video-provider=\"guardian.co.uk\"                data-video-poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2014/3/26/1395870727282/The-debate-for-Europe-Nic-016.jpg\"> <video data-media-id=\"gu-video-433083928\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2014/3/26/1395870725808/The-debate-for-Europe-Nic-015.jpg\"> <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2014/03/26/140327lbcdebatehighlights-16x9.mp4\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/webM/2014/03/26//140327lbcdebatehighlights.webm\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2014/03/26/140327lbcdebatehighlights_3gpSml16x9.3gp\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/HLS/2014/03/26/140327lbcdebatehighlights/140327lbcdebatehighlights.m3u8\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2014/03/26/140327lbcdebatehighlights_3gpLg16x9.3gp\"></source> </video> </figure>  <h2>Nigel Farage is significantly more popular than Nick Clegg</h2><p>This was the week of the long-awaited and much-hyped Europe <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2014/mar/26/nigel-farage-vs-nick-clegg-the-debate-for-europe-live\">debate</a> between the Lib Dem leader, Nick Clegg, and the Ukip leader, Nigel Farage. Clegg, the surprise success of the 2010 party leaders debates, went into the LBC encounter hoping that gravitas and facts would see him through, but, although the Westminster punditocracy was inclined to declare him the winner, YouGov’s snap poll showed that 57% of viewers (based on a representative sample of 1,000) thought Farage did best. Given the innate Euroscepticism of the electorate, perhaps this shouldn’t have come as a surprise. Only 36% thought Clegg emerged on top. Still, 36% is higher than 9%, the Lib Dems’ poll rating.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-embed\" data-alt=\"Debate polling\">  <iframe src=\"http://cf.datawrapper.de/N1wfP/4/\" frameborder=\"0\" allowtransparency=\"true\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" webkitallowfullscreen=\"webkitallowfullscreen\" mozallowfullscreen=\"mozallowfullscreen\" oallowfullscreen=\"oallowfullscreen\" msallowfullscreen=\"msallowfullscreen\" width=\"460\" height=\"400\"></iframe> <figcaption>Debate polling graphic</figcaption> </figure>  <p>YouGov also found that although Farage’s sweaty and slightly shouty anti-establishmentism won him the debate, he failed to persuade viewers that Britain should leave the EU. At the end of the programme those in favour of staying in still outnumbered those in favour of leaving. Next week they go through it all again on the BBC. Farage will want to lighten up a bit (his fury was unappealing), and Clegg will want to cut some of the waffle and sharpen his lines of attack. <b>Andrew Sparrow</b></p><h2>Candy Crush has pricked the tech bubble</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-c8bdfb9c-37bf-4c74-896c-9f486f0e4af5\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396005009552/1b817ea8-e117-4d9d-8010-4d40c82b00fc-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Candy Crush Saga\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>A character from Candy Crush Saga on the floor of the New York Stock Exchange. Photograph: Brendan McDermid/Reuters</figcaption> </figure>  <p>King Digital, which makes the blockbuster smartphone game Candy Crush, went from hero to zero during its closely watched <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/mar/26/candy-crush-king-digital-shares-collapse-ipo\">stock market debut</a>. On Tuesday it was worth $7bn, the most valuable UK digital company ever. The company and its investors, directors and staff sold millions of shares to banks and their customers at $22.50 apiece. By Wednesday, when the shares started changing hands on the New York Stock Exchange, the game was over. Sensing a second technology bubble, traders wiped $1bn from King’s value and it made history again, as one of the worst ever US flotations. <br></p>  <figure class=\"element element-embed\" data-alt=\"Candy crush\">  <iframe src=\"http://cf.datawrapper.de/oqgtT/1/\" frameborder=\"0\" allowtransparency=\"true\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" webkitallowfullscreen=\"webkitallowfullscreen\" mozallowfullscreen=\"mozallowfullscreen\" oallowfullscreen=\"oallowfullscreen\" msallowfullscreen=\"msallowfullscreen\" width=\"460\" height=\"400\"></iframe> <figcaption>Candy Crush share price graphic</figcaption> </figure>  <p>King was not alone in being dethroned: Twitter fell to its lowest price since December, and Facebook lost 7% after splurging $2bn on Oculus, which makes virtual reality goggles. Unease about the huge valuations placed on the darlings of the digital universe is spilling into the real world. <b>Juliette Garside</b></p><h2>There are 529 reasons to question Egypt’s democracy</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-9c451054-2500-4fb8-88f8-772f9ebcc332\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396005191132/6652a192-e526-4a50-81a2-edbdb7094371-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Minya\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Relatives of Morsi supporters outside court in Minya after the death sentences. Photograph: AFP/Getty Images</figcaption> </figure>  <p>Even amid a nationwide crackdown in which more than 2,500 people have been killed and nearly <a href=\"http://carnegieendowment.org/2014/03/24/egypt-s-unprecedented-instability-by-numbers/h5j3\">19,000 jailed</a>, the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/mar/24/egypt-morsi-supporters-death-sentence\">sentencing of 529 Egyptians to death</a> in one court case on Monday was nothing short of staggering. Amnesty said it was the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/mar/25/egypt-lawyers-boycott-mass-trial\">largest mass death sentence in modern memory</a>, and the UN said it contravened international law. The 529 were convicted of the murder of a single police officer after two court sessions that totalled less than an hour. At no point were lawyers allowed to defend their clients. <br></p><p>The whole exercise seemed to be aimed at intimidating the Muslim Brotherhood, the now-banned group that propelled the now-overthrown president Mohamed Morsi to power, and to whom the 529 were alleged – but not proven – to belong. More bad news could follow: a further 1,602 people will be tried en masse on similar charges by the same court within the next month. <b>Patrick Kingsley</b></p><h2>Police treat domestic violence as a second-class crime</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-daebe413-ce08-45c0-be09-f6374291cbee\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396010847315/343f9e2e-8169-4b63-bedf-b7d0cd84f70f-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Police officer\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>The investigation found poor attitudes among frontline officers. Photograph: Oli Scarff/Getty Images</figcaption> </figure>  <p>A <a href=\"http://www.hmic.gov.uk/publication/improving-the-police-response-to-domestic-abuse/\">report</a> from Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary revealed what campaigners have been saying for some time: domestic abuse is the poor relation when it comes to crime-fighting. In a six-month study of all 43 police forces in England and Wales, the HMIC concluded that only eight forces dealt appropriately with domestic abuse, which accounts for 8% of all recorded crime and costs society an estimated £15.7bn a year. The report said domestic violence was a “priority on paper but not in practice” for most forces, and described “alarming and unacceptable” weaknesses in investigating, collecting evidence and bringing offenders to justice, poor management and supervision, and ineffective training. <br></p><p>The investigation also found poor attitudes among frontline officers, exposing a macho and sexist culture that persists within policing. Some victims told inspectors that officers sided with the male perpetrators when answering calls for help. As if to illustrate the point, this week a domestic violence victim <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/mar/27/domestic-violence-victim-wins-damages-metropolitan-police\">won damages from the Metropolitan police</a> for gross abuse of power, after an officer on a 999 call plied her with drink and sexually exploited her. <b>Sandra Laville</b></p><h2>Ed Miliband is under pressure</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-78feb818-9e56-4010-9d9a-33dee5af9d7a\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396005328845/4f7d22ca-bcff-41ba-b050-1a60bcf106aa-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Ed Miliband\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Ed Miliband in the House of Commons. Photograph: PA</figcaption> </figure>  <p>Jittery Labourites started fretting last week after Ed Miliband <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/budget/10712417/Ed-Milibands-Budget-speech-was-repetitive-admits-Labour.html\">relied on stock lines</a> in a budget debate after the party was caught off-guard by a pensions shake-up that had been in the Tory manifesto. But boxing in the dark on budget day is tricky for every opposition leader, so most heads kept cool – until polls suggested <a href=\"http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/blog/archives/8686\">the party’s lead</a> was melting away. A letter signed by Labour factions of left and right who normally disagree urged <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/mar/23/labour-must-adopt-new-principles\">new principles</a> of “accountability”, “co-production” and “empowerment”, the sort of wonky words that Miliband sometimes gets teased for. Loftier commentators discerned an urge to transcend <a href=\"http://www.economist.com/blogs/blighty/2014/03/labours-new-divide\">Fabian centralism</a>; harder-nosed hacks spotted a ragbag of malcontents united only in having a problem with Ed. The draft letter pre-dated the polling wobble, but that is why got it such attention. <br></p><p>As the week ended, the agenda turned to more comfortable Miliband terrain – energy bills – so he’ll hope to feel less heat next week. In the meantime, some commentators (HT <a href=\"https://twitter.com/SamCoatesTimes\">@SamCoatesTimes</a>) were quick to point out the number of his friends piling on the pressure, including <a href=\"http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2014/03/sound-labour-silence-miliband-can-t-rely-tories-keep-hurting-cameron-him\">Rafael Behr in the New Statesman</a>, <a href=\"http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/columnists/article4045980.ece\">Jenni Russell in the Times</a>, <a href=\"http://labourlist.org/2014/03/labour-needs-to-go-bigger-and-bolder-not-just-to-win-but-to-govern-too/\">Mark Ferguson on Labour List</a>, <a href=\"http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2014/03/pmqs-review-milibands-price-freeze-saves-him-he-needs-new-hit\">George Eaton in the New Statesmen</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/mar/24/labour-tories-populus-comres-polls-jon-cruddas\">John Cruddas in the Guardian</a> and <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/ed-miliband/10722693/This-Labour-love-in-has-to-end-its-time-to-make-some-enemies.html\">Mary Riddell in the Telegraph</a>. <b>Tom Clark</b></p><h2>The Spanish don’t sleep</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-2251c6d7-feca-4b90-bda5-6b3becd683b7\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396010702942/b16df582-60c5-4e9c-bfd4-fa83b8426a6c-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"The Voice Kids\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>The finale of Spain's The Voice Kids finished at 1.25am. Photograph: Juan Naharro Gimenez/WireImage</figcaption> </figure>  <p>The country that introduced the world to siestas is having a very different kind of conversation about sleep these days. We learned that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/26/spain-working-hours-ending-siesta\">Spaniards sleep 53 minutes less than the European average</a>. One group says <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/mar/25/spanish-tv-airs-childrens-shows-past-bedtime-viewers-association\">prime-time TV is to blame</a>, pointing out that more than half of Spain’s top-rated television programmes finish later than midnight. Even the most popular children’s shows don’t start until late into the night, meaning that on any given weeknight nearly 600,000 Spanish children aged four to 12 are watching TV after 10pm. Last week when the finale of The Voice Kids finished at 1.25am, more than 130,000 Spanish children were still watching. <br></p><p>The Association of Communication Users is demanding that Spanish TV networks move children’s programming earlier. They’ve joined the many who are working to set Spaniards on a path towards better sleep habits, whether it be by rolling the clocks back an hour or introducing a standard 9-5 workday. As one campaigner explained: “We’re in a country beset by crisis, which requires everyone to put in a little extra effort to maintain high levels of commitment and work efficiency.” <b>Ashifa Kassam</b></p><h2>Heat is on for the big six <br></h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-58d142a2-a555-446a-a701-06c7437c938a\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396008801454/1eec11bb-ff48-472f-a803-4baed90392d0-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Gas rings\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Dual fuel prices are up 24% in four years. Photograph: Linda Nylind for the Guardian</figcaption> </figure>  <p>Years of consumer frustration and political finger-pointing over the energy market were brought to a head as Ofgem announced it would refer the big six energy suppliers to a full competition inquiry. In its <a href=\"https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/ofgem-publications/86804/assessmentdocumentpublished.pdf\">referral (pdf)</a> to the newly created Competition and Markets Authority, Ofgem raised a number of concerns including <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/mar/27/ofgem-energy-report-key-points\">“tacit” co-ordination of price increases</a>, and flagged problems over the combination of power generation and supply within the same six firms. Ofgem hinted that this could lead to breakups, while the owner of British Gas said the ensuing investment paralysis could lead to blackouts. </p>  <figure class=\"element element-embed\" data-alt=\"Fuel bills\">  <iframe class=\"fenced\" srcdoc=\"&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;/head&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://static.guim.co.uk/ni/1396010383392/Dual-fuel-bills_WEB.svg&quot; style=&quot;width:100%;&quot; &quot;height:100%;&quot;&gt;&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;\"></iframe> <figcaption>Energy prices graphic</figcaption> </figure>  <p>Ofgem is at last offering to put the debate to bed but it will take at least two years before the inquiry reaches a final verdict. The vital fact to remember: average dual fuel prices, where a customer takes gas and electricity from the same supplier, have risen by 24% between 2009 and 2013. <b>Dan Milmo</b></p><h2>The BBC is going highbrow</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-d3867c24-ce5a-4632-a654-a369be0187a8\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396005734316/e3bda791-44fc-4632-9363-bc56fe3d59c2-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Tony Hall\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Tony Hall, the BBC director general. Photograph: Lewis Whyld/PA</figcaption> </figure>  <p>The BBC’s director general, Tony Hall, announced the corporation’s “strongest commitment to arts in a generation”. Hall’s <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/mar/25/bbc-arts-coverage-extra-3m\">bumper arts package</a> – lots more Shakespeare and a “front-row seat” at arts events up and down the country – was no surprise coming from a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/nov/22/bbc-tony-hall-appointed-new-director-general\">former chief executive of the Royal Opera House</a>. It was handily timed as the BBC gets down to the business of charter renewal and securing from the government – whoever is in power after next May’s general election – an increase in the licence fee.  Younger viewers could be forgiven for thinking their dedicated BBC3 TV channel (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/mar/06/bbc3-closure-bbc1-drama\">going online-only next year</a>) has been sacrificed on the altar of high art. Richard III and Henry VI <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2011/may/10/cabe-girl-snog-marry-avoid\">go down better with MPs than Snog, Marry, Avoid?</a>. <br></p><p>But it didn’t last long. Like a storyline from <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/mar/25/in-praise-of-w1a\">BBC2’s cod-documentary W1A</a>, 48 hours later the corporation confirmed it was <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/mar/27/bbc-axes-review-show-tony-hall\">axing its 20-year-old topical arts roundup The Review Show</a>. Taxi for the DG? It would be entirely appropriate, after the BBC’s latest expense accounts revealed that BBC bosses had spent more than £20,000 on cabs in three months. <b>John Plunkett</b><br></p><h2>The ocean is mind-bogglingly vast</h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-5c9e63eb-46c8-4f59-bbf7-113b2a989e6b\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396007933754/1ca749f9-3af6-4d77-b781-2fc26da9f417-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Indian Ocean\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>RAAF Flight Lieutenant Russell Adams looks out from the cockpit of a AP-3C Orion during a search mission over the southern Indian Ocean. Photograph: Paul Kane/AFP/Getty Images</figcaption> </figure>  <p>The search for MH370 continues in the Indian Ocean, which as the world’s third largest ocean accounts for around a fifth of all surface water. The patch of the southern ocean that crews are scouring for any trace of the missing Malaysia Airlines plane covers almost 470,000 nautical square miles, making it roughly the size of Alaska, according to Associated Press. Worse still for searchers, it is prone to fast currents, strong winds and high waves even in relatively calm weather. </p>  <figure class=\"element element-embed\" data-alt=\"Indian Ocean search\">  <iframe class=\"fenced\" srcdoc=\"&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;/head&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://static.guim.co.uk/ni/1395915710343/MH370_search_area_compariso.svg&quot; style=&quot;width:100%;&quot; &quot;height:100%;&quot;&gt;&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;\"></iframe> <figcaption>Plane search graphic</figcaption> </figure>  <p>The search zone is also remote, 1,000 miles from the nearest land and 1,500 miles south-west of Perth, the closest major city. Flying there from Australia takes around four hours, leaving little fuel for the search. But to truly understand the ocean’s magnitude you need to consider its depth as well as its breadth – on average around 4km, and at its deepest point twice that. <b>Tania Branigan</b></p><h2>Phrase of the week<br></h2>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-023e03e2-f168-4a21-9226-4b233c38aa85\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396007247554/172ceb97-56e7-4311-a0c4-92b261befb73-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Gwyneth Paltrow\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Gwyneth Paltrow. Photograph: Matt Baron/Rex</figcaption> </figure>  <p>This week we learned that Gwyneth Paltrow and Chris Martin did not, in fact, invent the term <a href=\"http://www.goop.com/journal/be/conscious-uncoupling\">“conscious uncoupling”</a> – that honour goes to “life coach, psychotherapist and relationship expert” <a href=\"http://katherinewoodwardthomas.com/about-katherine/\">Katherine Woodward Thomas</a>, who came up with the idea of a course to help couples decouple without arguments over who gets to keep the bedside tables. </p><p>Woodward Thomas offers a free online seminar in the <a href=\"http://evolvingwisdom.com/consciousuncoupling/free-online-class/\">Art of Conscious Completion</a> for those keen to move on from heartbreak. Otherwise, she warns, “it can take decades, and for others still, the wound never heals. They never find love again. They never feel that kind of joy again.” The Paltrow-Martin uncoupling has clearly had an effect, at least on Woodward Thomas’s book sales: her rank in paper copies has gone up from 9,381st to 7,962nd in the UK this week, and her Kindle ranking on Amazon from 42,761st to 17,943. Not earth-shattering, true, but, hey, she’s not bitter. <b>Claire Phipps</b></p>","headline":"Ten things we learned this week","trailText":"From Clegg v Farage to Paltrow minus Martin, via Egypt, Ed Miliband and the energy market – a roundup of the week's news<br>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/28/1396007651583/dcd7acdc-98af-446f-82da-975eb980fe63-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"1918","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-31T13:30:40+01:00"},"webUrl":"ht