ing liver transplant story.</p><p>I live and work in the north-east of England, but this phenomenon is also observable “where you are”. These small, seemingly unconnected stories are the atoms of local news – or at least, the scientific matter we’ve accepted as immutable - that comprise local TV, radio, newspapers or brochures that masquerade as magazines.</p><p>But it doesn’t have to be that way: which is why I’m part of a team using <a href=\"https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/ianwylie/northern-correspondent\">Kickstarter</a> to launch a magazine of longform, narrative journalism in the north east. A New Yorker in Newcastle … if you can imagine such a thing.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-82b6ad0a-566f-48da-8b5f-02a5bbb2d94e\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/27/1395930257914/e61b8902-7e0a-4b12-ba3d-2c26f3161cd9-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Northern Correspondent\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Northern Correspondent Photograph: /Northern Correspondent</figcaption> </figure>  <p>Longform. Local. Polar opposites, no? My corner of England is home to two and a half million people, two and a half million people with stories to tell. And within that two and a half million we’re betting there’s more than a few who crave reporting about their region that’s more substantial, stimulating and satisfying than what’s currently on offer.</p><p>It’s a region, like yours, that deserves and needs its stories to be told and heard in depth, but the opportunities to tell and hear these stories are fast diminishing. In the past decade, more than 20% of the UK’s local newspapers have closed. Cuts in the numbers of journalists and the production of local newspapers or regional programmes many miles from the communities they serve mean huge “news gaps” are opening up. </p><p>The job of “northern correspondent” is under threat as news organisations chase global rather local audiences. In 1976 the Guardian had 94 journalists based in Manchester. It now has only two staff reporters in England who are not based in London. “We are all competing in an increasingly noisy media world and it is only going to get louder and more crowded,” the Independent’s northern correspondent, Jonathan Brown, tells me. “You have to work harder to get your stories heard.”</p><p>I recall my excitement when, in 1994, I realised my new 14.4kb-a-second Motorola modem, Apple Powerbook and Netscape browser could connect me to anyone in the world. The internet, email and desktop publishing meant journalists like me didn’t need to be in London or New York to publish or be published. </p><p>Two decades later, our media industries remain stubbornly London-centric. Economic forces, interests and arguments of scale and consolidation have suppressed those opportunities and dreams. </p><p>This is not news. The career path for a journalist has traditionally been local to regional, then national and international. Only a fool like me swims the other way. I worked 16 years for the Guardian in the capital, commuting back and forth from Newcastle until a tiny voice in my head told me I was too old to be sleeping on my London friends’ sofas and airbeds.</p><p>And as consumers of news, the social media habits we’ve developed in recent years ensure we’re more likely to know what’s happening in New York or New Zealand than Newcastle.</p><p>And yet –in spite of, or maybe because of this globalisation – we’re increasingly keen to source other products and services locally, support our local butcher or greengrocer. There’s a greater desire, once we step away from our tablets and laptops, to step back into the real world of communities and neighbours. We know intuitively that this is “a good thing” to do. </p><p>At the same time, we’re observing a growing appetite for longer form, more narrative journalism that is willing and able to engage readers’ interests in important subjects and themes across three, four or five thousand words.</p><p>Northern Correspondent is a small group of journalists and story-tellers, writers, photographers, illustrators, film-makers and broadcasters who are passionate about telling stories of the people and places of the north east. We’re going to tell those stories in whichever medium is best for telling each story. Our journey is beginning with a printed magazine, because we love the written word, but we plan to make documentary films and radio programmes too. </p><p>A New Yorker for Newcastle - sounds like a joke. I think I just heard some of my London-based editors guffaw. But that’s OK. “Getting chippy about the north and the raw deal it gets doesn't appeal to readers elsewhere and isn't good for anyone's own soul either,” is the advice from Martin Wainwright, a former Guardian northern correspondent.</p><p>Maybe we’ll discover you cannot change the laws of journalism physics – that the gravitational pull of London makes it impossible to create and sustain a credible news ecosystem elsewhere.</p><p>But it’s worth a crack, isn’t it?</p>","headline":"Welcome the Northern Correspondent: a New Yorker for Newcastle?","trailText":"Fed up with their local news offering, a group of top flight journalists have decided to launch a new magazine of long-form narrative journalism in the north-east of England. Editor <b>Ian Wylie</b> explains more","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/27/1395929942273/06a730b7-9efc-4482-b960-ef663bc00adf-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"803","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-04-04T07:00:26Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/the-northerner/2014/mar/28/the-northern-correspondent-a-new-yorker-for-newcastle","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/uk-news/the-northerner/2014/mar/28/the-northern-correspondent-a-new-yorker-for-newcastle","tags":[{"id":"uk/the-northerner","webTitle":"The Northerner","type":"blog","sectionId":"uk-news","se