 should be given a limited window to find a job before being required to leave.\"</p><p>Cameron told BBC Radio Derby on Thursday: \"We are doing what the Germans are doing, which is [to] introduce new rules that you cannot immediately claim benefits if you come here, and if you are an EU citizen and not looking for work and claiming benefits then you can be removed to your country of origin. We'll look very closely if the Germans want to take this further&nbsp;… [It is] absolutely right to say that we should work with the Germans and others to tighten up the rules so that there is free movement to come here and get a job but not free movement to come and claim benefits.\"</p><p>The proposals would involve changing German law within the context of existing EU laws. The Germans appear to be going further than current British plans by denying residency to jobless migrants after three months. But Open Europe said Britain would go further by denying re-entry to those who did not have a job after 12 months. Germany would only deny re-entry to those involved in fraud.</p>","headline":"David Cameron welcomes German proposals on EU migration rules","trailText":"German government reportedly plans to remove residency rights from EU immigrants if they fail to find work after three months","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/27/1395950711453/David-Cameron-has-been-ta-005.jpg","wordcount":"366","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-30T19:05:49Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/mar/27/david-cameron-welcomes-german-proposals-eu-migrant-rules","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/uk-news/2014/mar/27/david-cameron-welcomes-german-proposals-eu-migrant-rules","tags":[{"id":"uk/immigration","webTitle":"Immigration and asylum","type":"keyword","sectionId":"uk-news","sectionName":"UK news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/immigration","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/uk/immigration"