e","body":"<p>A jury has found Nigel Evans not guilty of one count of sexual assault after a judge ruled that the former deputy Speaker had not kissed a man he is alleged to have made a pass at in a parliamentary corridor.</p><p>The judge at Preston crown court instructed the foreman of the jury to return a verdict of not guilty of one of the nine charges faced by Evans. Mr Justice King said on Thursday that the prosecution evidence relating to an incident in which the MP, 56, is alleged to have tried to kiss a 27-year-old parliamentary worker in 2009-10 did not amount to sexual assault.</p><p>He amended the charge to attempted sexual assault after the complainant conceded under oath that Evans, allegedly drunk after spending time in the Strangers' Bar, had tried to kiss him but stopped when he said \"no\".</p><p>Evans denied all of the charges against him as he gave evidence for the first time on Thursday, calling one of the sexual assault allegations absurd.</p><p>He was asked by his barrister, Peter Wright QC, whether he had \"ever taken a man by the genitals in the Strangers' Bar as a form of introduction, one to the other?\" as one of the seven complainants had earlier told the court. Evans replied: \"No. It's as absurd as it sounds.\"</p><p>He also denied forcing himself on a man after tricking him into a kitchenette at his quarters in the houses of parliament after becoming deputy Speaker in 2010. His kitchen \"would not be high on my tour of the palace of Westminster\", he said.</p><p>He admitted having sex with a young man who accused him of raping him at his constituency home last year but insisted the sex was \"absolutely with consent\".</p><p>Asked by Wright about his family background, Evans said he was born in Swansea and educated at local schools. As soon as his head could be seen above the counter, he was involved in helping to run the family grocery shop, started by his grandfather in the 1930s, which he described as something like the store in TV sitcom Open All Hours.</p><p>He said he thought having all the newspapers in the shop sparked his interest in current affairs and politics, and he joined the Young Conservatives at the age of 17.</p><p>\"I always thought it was God's little joke – he made me born in Swansea and born a Tory. There's not many Tories in Swansea.\"</p><p>He told the court he was unsuccessful several times in running for office as both a councillor and an MP until he was finally elected as MP for Ribble Valley in 1992.</p><p>Asked why he did not go public about his sexuality until December 2010, in an article in the Mail on Sunday, Evans said he didn't want to upset his mother, who died in 2009.</p><p>\"My mother was in her 80s and there was no right time and I just didn't want to upset her. I didn't know how she would take it,\" said Evans, adding that in hindsight he wished he had told her. \"On reflection I think she would have taken it rather well. I'm sorry I didn't do it earlier.\"</p><p>The prosecution have claimed that Evans only went public about being gay after one of the alleged victims, a politics student, made a complaint to the higher echelons of the party in 2009. Patrick McLoughlin, then the opposition chief whip and now the transport secretary, told the court he advised Evans to go public about his sexuality after hearing of the student's allegations.</p><p>The case continues.</p>","headline":"Nigel Evans found not guilty on one sexual assault charge","trailText":"Judge instructs jury on verdict after saying evidence over MP's alleged kiss only amounts to attempted sexual assault","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/27/1395945207923/Nigel-Evans-arrives-at-Pr-004.jpg","wordcount":"586","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-30T17:36:08Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/mar/27/nigel-evans-not-guilty-one-sexual-assault-charge-mp","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/uk-news/2014/mar/27/nige